What is Ammonium Sulphate?

Ammonium Sulphate is an inorganic chemical compound with the chemical formula (NH₄)₂SO₄. It contains approximately 21% nitrogen in the form of ammonium ions and 24% sulphur as sulphate ions, making it an important dual-nutrient fertilizer widely used in agriculture.

Besides its extensive agricultural applications, ammonium sulphate is also utilized in mining, food processing, water treatment, industrial chemicals, and as an agricultural spray adjuvant to improve pesticide effectiveness.

Modern ammonium sulphate production involves several manufacturing routes including:

Caprolactam By-Product Production for cost-efficient fertilizer manufacturing
Coke-Oven Gas Recovery Process
Synthetic Ammonia-Based Production
Flue Gas Desulphurization (FGD) Recovery Technologies
Advanced Granulation & Prilling Technologies for improved handling
Precision Nutrient Formulations for modern agriculture
By supplying both nitrogen and sulphur simultaneously, ammonium sulphate improves crop productivity, enhances nutrient uptake, corrects sulphur deficiencies, supports soil fertility management, and contributes to sustainable agricultural production.

