What Are the Key Drivers of the Global Ammonium Sulphate Market?

1. Rising Global Demand for Food Security

The growing global population continues increasing pressure on agricultural production and crop yields.

Ammonium sulphate has become an essential fertilizer for crops requiring both nitrogen and sulphur, including cereals, oilseeds, corn, wheat, rice, and canola. Increasing fertilizer consumption across Asia-Pacific and Latin America continues driving global market expansion as governments prioritize food security and sustainable farming practices.

2. Cost-Effective By-Product Production

More than half of global ammonium sulphate production is generated as a by-product of caprolactam manufacturing used in nylon production.

This production route offers manufacturers an economically attractive and environmentally sustainable method of fertilizer production while supporting circular economy initiatives through efficient utilization of industrial by-products.

Its stable supply chain and lower production costs continue strengthening market competitiveness.

3. Growing Adoption of Precision Agriculture

Modern farming techniques increasingly emphasize balanced nutrient management and efficient fertilizer utilization.

Ammonium sulphate's excellent water solubility, low salt index, compatibility with fertigation systems, and suitability for foliar applications make it increasingly valuable in precision agriculture and high-efficiency crop management programs.

